const TEMPLATE = "# prompts/report.md — teaching report (end of session)\n\nCalled once when phase hits \"done\" or the student ends the session. Model\nclaude-sonnet-4-6, temperature 0.2, max_tokens 1200. Output is markdown for the\nteacher view. Store raw markdown in DB keyed to session.\n\n---\n\nYou write a one-page teaching report for a teacher. The student just attempted to\nteach a concept to Milo, a simulated classmate. Your ONLY sources of truth are the\ninputs below. Never invent quotes. Never soften an unresolved gap into a positive.\n\nCONCEPT PACK:\n{{PACK_JSON}}\n\nFINAL STATE:\n{{STATE_JSON}}\n\nFULL TRANSCRIPT:\n{{TRANSCRIPT}}\n\nLEARNER MEMORY (past session summaries; may be empty):\n{{LEARNER_MEMORY}}\n\nWrite exactly these sections, plain and concrete, no praise inflation:\n\n## Teaching report — {{LEARNER_NAME}} · {{CONCEPT_TITLE}} · {{DATE}}\n\n**In one line:** did the student demonstrate mechanistic understanding, procedural\nknowledge only, or neither.\n\n**Misconception evidence.** One short block per misconception in the pack:\n- Status: Resolved / Not resolved.\n- If resolved: the evidence quote (verbatim from transcript, in quotation marks) and\n  one line on why it shows mechanism.\n- If not resolved: what the student said instead (quote the closest attempt) and what\n  was missing (e.g. \"restated the rule, never explained why the reciprocal works\").\n\n**Explanation quality** (1–4 each, one-line justification, be stingy with 4s):\n- Accuracy · Completeness · Use of examples/analogies\n\n**Reteach next.** Max 2 items, concrete and misconception-specific (\"revisit why\ndividing by a number under 1 grows the result, e.g. how many half-cups in 3 cups\"),\nnever generic (\"review fractions\").\n\n**Trend.** ONLY if LEARNER MEMORY is non-empty: 2–3 sentences on trajectory across\nsessions — is the student moving from procedural restatement toward causal\nexplanation, do the same misconception categories recur, which teaching moves (their\nanalogies) are working. Cite session numbers. If memory is empty, omit this section\nentirely.\n\n**Suggested next concept.** One line, justified by what was resolved today.\n";
const PACKS = {"fractions_division":{"id":"fractions_division","title":"Dividing fractions","grade_band":"5-6","ground_truth":"a/b ÷ c/d asks how many groups of c/d fit into a/b. Multiplying by the reciprocal d/c computes that count because the reciprocal expresses 'how many of this piece per whole'. Dividing by a number less than 1 yields a result larger than the dividend. Only the divisor (second fraction) is inverted; inverting the dividend answers a different question. 3/4 ÷ 1/2 = 3/4 × 2/1 = 3/2.","learner_opening":"Okay so we're doing dividing fractions and honestly? Keep-change-flip feels like a magic spell. Why would flipping the second fraction upside down do ANYTHING? Who decided that?","misconceptions":[{"id":"m1","belief":"Flip-and-multiply is an arbitrary trick with no reason behind it.","resolution_criteria":"Student explains the causal mechanism: division means 'how many of the divisor fit into the dividend', and multiplying by the reciprocal counts those fits (the reciprocal expresses pieces-per-whole). A worked instance (e.g. how many halves fit in 3/4) satisfies this if the why is explicit. Does NOT count: restating keep-change-flip, saying 'division is the opposite of multiplication' without the fitting/counting mechanism, or asserting it 'just works'.","probe":"But WHY does flipping do anything? Like I get that it gives the right answer on the worksheet, but it feels like the math version of abracadabra.","failure_mode":"Attempts 3/4 ÷ 1/2 by multiplying straight across without flipping anything: 'so it's 3 times 1 and 4 times 2... 3/8?'"},{"id":"m2","belief":"Dividing always makes the answer smaller.","resolution_criteria":"Student explains WHY dividing by a number smaller than 1 gives a larger result: smaller pieces means more of them fit into the same amount (or equivalent mechanism). A concrete instance (e.g. how many half-pizzas in 3 pizzas is 6) counts if the more-pieces-fit reasoning is stated. Does NOT count: merely asserting 'the answer can be bigger' without the why.","probe":"Wait, hold on. 3/2 is BIGGER than 3/4. Division is supposed to make things smaller, that's like... the whole point of dividing? Something's broken.","failure_mode":"Computes 3/2 but rejects it because it grew: 'that can't be right, dividing makes stuff smaller... I must've messed up, it's probably 3/8.'"},{"id":"m3","belief":"It doesn't matter which fraction you flip.","resolution_criteria":"Student explains that flipping the dividend changes which question is being asked (how many 3/4s fit in 1/2 vs how many 1/2s fit in 3/4), i.e. only the divisor is rewritten as its reciprocal because it is the piece being counted. Does NOT count: 'you just always flip the second one' stated as a rule.","probe":"Okay but if flipping is so great, could I flip the FIRST one instead? Flipping is flipping, right?","failure_mode":"Flips the dividend: 'so 4/3 times 1/2... that's 4/6, which is 2/3?'"}],"check_problem":{"question":"What is 3/4 ÷ 1/2?","correct_answer":"3/2 (one and a half)","correct_reasoning":"How many halves fit into three quarters? One half fits, and the leftover quarter is half of a half — so 1.5 halves. 3/4 × 2/1 = 3/2.","aha_hint":"Milo restates: dividing is asking how many of the second thing FIT in the first thing, flipping just counts the pieces, and that's why the answer can grow when the pieces are small."}},"photosynthesis":{"id":"photosynthesis","title":"Photosynthesis","grade_band":"6-8","ground_truth":"Photosynthesis builds glucose from CO2 and water using light energy; the carbon in the plant's mass comes mainly from CO2 in the air, not from soil. Plants also respire, consuming O2 and releasing CO2, but in light they photosynthesize faster than they respire, for a net O2 release. Light is an energy source, not a material ingredient; the atoms of the sugar come from CO2 and water.","learner_opening":"So plants make their food from sunlight, which is kind of amazing but also confusing. Sunlight is the food? Or the sunlight goes into the dirt somehow? Where does the actual plant STUFF come from?","misconceptions":[{"id":"m1","belief":"Plants get their mass/food primarily from the soil.","resolution_criteria":"Student explains that the bulk of a plant's material (the carbon in sugars and structure) comes from CO2 in the air, with atoms from CO2 and water assembled into glucose. Does NOT count: 'plants need soil/nutrients' (true but not the mechanism), or naming CO2 without saying it becomes the plant's material.","probe":"But plants grow OUT of soil, so the plant stuff has to be coming up from the dirt, right? That's where I'd put my money.","failure_mode":"Explains a growing tree gains mass because 'it pulls the material up from the soil through the roots.'"},{"id":"m2","belief":"Light is a physical ingredient/material that becomes part of the sugar.","resolution_criteria":"Student distinguishes energy from matter: light provides the ENERGY to build bonds, but the ATOMS come from CO2 and water. Does NOT count: 'plants use sunlight' without separating the energy role from the material source.","probe":"So the sunlight is like... one of the ingredients? Like flour in a cake? It goes IN the sugar?","failure_mode":"Lists the ingredients of glucose as 'sunlight, water, and air' as if light is a material."},{"id":"m3","belief":"Plants only photosynthesize and never respire (or only respire at night).","resolution_criteria":"Student explains plants respire all the time (using O2, releasing CO2), and that in light photosynthesis outpaces respiration for a NET O2 release. Does NOT count: 'plants give off oxygen' with no mention of respiration also happening.","probe":"Wait, do plants breathe? I thought they were the opposite of us — we do CO2, they do oxygen, like we're a team. So they never use oxygen?","failure_mode":"Claims plants 'only breathe in CO2 and only breathe out oxygen, they never use oxygen at all.'"}],"check_problem":{"question":"A tree gains 500 kg of mass over years. Where did most of that mass come from?","correct_answer":"Mostly from carbon dioxide in the air (carbon atoms), plus water.","correct_reasoning":"CO2 from the air is captured and its carbon built into sugars and structural molecules; light supplies energy, not atoms; soil supplies water and trace minerals but not the bulk mass.","aha_hint":"Milo restates: the tree is basically built out of AIR — carbon from CO2 — with sunlight as the energy to put it together, not as an ingredient."}}};

const CORS = {
  "access-control-allow-origin": "*",
  "access-control-allow-methods": "POST, OPTIONS",
  "access-control-allow-headers": "content-type, authorization"
};

function json(obj, status) {
  return new Response(JSON.stringify(obj), {
    status,
    headers: { "content-type": "application/json", ...CORS }
  });
}

export default async function handler(req, ctx) {
  if (req.method === "OPTIONS") return new Response(null, { status: 204, headers: CORS });
  if (req.method !== "POST") return json({ error: "POST only" }, 405);
  try {
    const { pack_id, pack: dynamicPack, state, transcript, learner_memory, learner_name, agent_name } = await req.json();
    const pack = PACKS[pack_id] || (dynamicPack && dynamicPack.misconceptions ? dynamicPack : null);
    if (!pack) return json({ error: "unknown pack: " + pack_id }, 400);
    const rename = t => (agent_name && agent_name !== "Milo") ? t.split("Milo").join(agent_name) : t;
    if (!state || !transcript) return json({ error: "state and transcript are required" }, 400);

    const date = new Date().toLocaleDateString("en-US", { year: "numeric", month: "long", day: "numeric" });
    const prompt = rename(TEMPLATE
      .replace("{{PACK_JSON}}", JSON.stringify(pack, null, 2))
      .replace("{{STATE_JSON}}", JSON.stringify(state, null, 2))
      .replace("{{TRANSCRIPT}}", transcript)
      .replace("{{LEARNER_MEMORY}}", JSON.stringify(learner_memory || []))
      .replace("{{LEARNER_NAME}}", learner_name || "Student")
      .replace("{{CONCEPT_TITLE}}", pack.title)
      .replace("{{DATE}}", date));

    const res = await fetch(
      ctx.env.BUTTERBASE_API_URL + "/v1/" + ctx.env.BUTTERBASE_APP_ID + "/chat/completions",
      {
        method: "POST",
        headers: {
          "content-type": "application/json",
          authorization: "Bearer " + ctx.env.BUTTERBASE_API_KEY
        },
        body: JSON.stringify({
          model: "anthropic/claude-sonnet-4.6",
          max_tokens: 1200,
          temperature: 0.2,
          messages: [{ role: "user", content: prompt }]
        })
      }
    );
    if (!res.ok) return json({ error: "gateway " + res.status + ": " + (await res.text()) }, 502);

    const data = await res.json();
    const report = ((data.choices && data.choices[0] && data.choices[0].message.content) || "")
      .replace(/^\s*\u0060\u0060\u0060(markdown)?/i, "").replace(/\u0060\u0060\u0060\s*$/, "").trim();
    if (!report) return json({ error: "empty report from model" }, 502);
    return json({ report, _usage: data.usage }, 200);
  } catch (err) {
    return json({ error: String((err && err.message) || err) }, 500);
  }
}
